# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aberdeenshire-council
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The election used the 10 wards created by the Formation Electoral Arrangements in 1974.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Each ward elected one councillor using first-past-the-post voting.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Banff and Buchan was a non-partisan district.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Only a few members of political parties contested the election and all but three of the 18 seats were won by independents.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Prior to 1974, the area that was to become Banff and Buchan, was split between two counties – the County of Banff and the County of Aberdeen.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Within that were five of the 11 burghs of the County of Banff (Aberchirder, Banff, Fraserburgh, Macduff and Portsoy) and two of the 10 burghs of the County of Aberdeen (Peterhead, Rosehearty and Turriff).
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] These were all small burghs so the burgh council had limited powers which included some control over planning as well as local taxation, building control, housing, lighting and drainage with the rest of the local government responsibility falling to the county council.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973 implemented most of the recommendations in the Wheatly Report.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The northeastern part of the County of Baff which included the five burghs was combined with the northern part of the County of Abrdeen and was placed into the Banff and Buchan district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Banff and Buchan, like the other three districts in Grampian excluding the City of Aberdeen, was non-partisan and controlled by Independent candidates who won all 15 of the 18 seats.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] The Conservatives controlled the regional council which held its first election on the same day.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-banff-and-buchan-district-council-election] Across Scotland, Labour won the most votes, the most seats and the most councils of any party.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The election used the 12 wards created by the Formation Electoral Arrangements in 1974.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The council was left in no overall control following the election.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Independent candidates won six of the 12 seats.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The Conservatives were the largest party after they took four seats while the Liberals won two seats.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Prior to 1974, the area that was to become Gordon, contained were five of the 10 burghs of the County of Aberdeen (Ellon, Huntly, Inverurie, Kintore and Oldmeldrum).
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] The central part of the County of Aberdeen which included the five burghs was placed into the Gordon district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Gordon was left in no overall control following the election but, like the three of the other districts in Grampian except the City of Aberdeen, saw more independent candidates elected than political parties.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-gordon-district-council-election] Independents took six seats, the Conservatives won four seats and the Liberals won the remaining two seats.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Kincardine and Deeside was a non-partisan district.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Only a few political party members contested the election and all but two of the 12 seats were won by independents.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] The remaining two seats were won by the Conservatives.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Prior to 1974, the area that was to become Kincardine and Deeside, was split between two counties – the County of Aberdeen and the County of Kincardine.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Within that were one of the 10 burghs of the County of Aberdeen (Ballater) and all four of the burghs of the County of Kincardine (Banchory, Inverbervie, Laurencekirk and Stonehaven).
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] The County of Kincardine which included the four burghs was combined with the southern area including Ballater from the County of Aberdeen and was placed into the Kincardine and Deeside district within the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1974-kincardine-and-deeside-district-council-election] Kincardine and Deeside, like three of the other districts in Grampian except the City of Aberdeen, was non-partisan and controlled by independent candidates who won all but two of the 12 seats.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The **fourth election to Grampian Regional Council** was held on 8 May 1986 as part of the wider 1986 Scottish regional elections.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The election saw the Conservatives suffering heavy losses, which were in turn picked up by the various other parties.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The Labour Party emerged as the single largest force on the 57 seat council, although all parties fell well short of the 29 seats needed for a majority.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The election was particularly devastating for the Conservatives in the region given that they had controlled the council since its creation in 1974.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] Following the election control of the council was undertaken by a minority administration composed of Independent, SNP, and SDP-Liberal Alliance councillors.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1986-grampian-regional-council-election] The councils new convenor was the Independent councillor Geoffrey Hadley.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1990-grampian-regional-council-election] The **1990 Grampian Regional Council election**, the fifth election to Grampian Regional Council, was held on 3 May 1990 as part of the wider 1990 Scottish regional elections.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1990-grampian-regional-council-election] The election saw Labour take the most seats, with the Conservatives falling sharply to finish fourth in terms of councillors.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1994-grampian-regional-council-election] The **1994 Grampian Regional Council election**, the sixth and final election to Grampian Regional Council, was held on 5 May 1994 as part of the wider 1994 Scottish regional elections.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/1994-grampian-regional-council-election] The election saw the Liberal Democrats take the most seats, although the Scottish National Party had a higher number of votes.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The Aberdeenshire council area was created in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts which had been created in 1975, replacing them with single-tier council areas.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Aberdeenshire covered the area of the abolished Banff and Buchan, Gordon and Kincardine and Deeside districts, all of which had been part of the Grampian region.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] It is named after the historic county of Aberdeenshire, but covers a larger area, also including most of the historic county of Kincardineshire and eastern parts of the historic county of Banffshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The council is the fifth largest Scottish council by number of councillors, having 70 members.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The council has devolved power to six area committees: Banff and Buchan; Buchan; Formartine; Garioch; Marr; and Kincardine and Mearns.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Each area committee takes decisions on local issues such as planning applications, and the split is meant to reflect the diverse circumstances of each area.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Following the 2017 election a coalition of the Conservatives, Liberal Democrats and some of the independent councillors formed to run the council.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The same parties continued running the council in coalition following the 2022 election.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The first election to the council was held in 1995.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] It initially operated as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Aberdeenshire Council has been under no overall control since its creation.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The role of provost is largely ceremonial in Aberdeenshire.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Of the independent councillors, seven form the 'Administration Independents' group, which forms part of the council's administration in coalition with the Conservatives and Liberal Democrats.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Two Conservative councillors who defected to Reform UK in October 2024 were the party's first representatives in Scotland.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The council is based at Woodhill House in Aberdeen, outside the council's own territory.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] The building was completed in 1977 for the former Grampian Regional Council.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Since 2007 elections have been held every five years under the single transferable vote system, introduced by the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004.
[src:aberdeenshire-council/aberdeenshire-council] Map of the area's ward (2017 configuration).
